Project Description: Timor-Leste has made great progress in education since independence. There have been some significant increases of total enrollment in basic education and government expenditure. School grants have led to the abolition of school fees, and infrastructural improvements have increased access opportunities. However, there are still many challenges. Among others: There is a large access gap between urban and rural areas; learning outcomes of Timorese students remain a serious concern; a majority of teacher is of below the required qualification (in addition to high absenteeism rates, high proportion of voluntary teachers, and a major teacher retirement looming). In addition, the country is also challenged to have a skilled workforce available to help drive productivity and economic growth over the coming decade. To provide a more comprehensive evidence to the Government of Timor Leste to develop and implement policies which will lead to improved access and learning for children and youth, four additional activities will be implemented: 1. Systems Approach for Better Education Results (SABER) on Early Childhood and Development and Engaging the Private Sector; 2. Early Grade Reading Assessment III. 3. School Survey II. This is to take a comprehensive portrait of governance, physical facilities, and teaching and learning quality issues at school level. 4. Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET)/Skills Toward Employment and Productivity (STEP). A survey will be conducted to assess skills demand and supply in the adult population to identify skills mismatches and inform education and training policies. 5. In addition, a Knowledge Sharing Forum will be conducted on an annual basis to promote dissemination and exchange of analytical work and foster high-level policy discussions around education challenges and bottlenecks.
Project title: P147838/TF: Education Sector Policy Advisory Support

Project Description: The Timor-Leste Ministry of Education has made significant efforts to prepare a comprehensive and evidence-based sector strategy reflecting the Millennium Development goals. The National Education Strategic Plan could be said to represent 'best practice' in education strategic planning in a fragile state context. The National Education Strategic Plan offers a vision for education and seeks to achieve universal basic education completion by 2030, gender equity in access and management by 2015, and elimination of illiteracy among 15-24 year olds by 2015. Timor-Leste has made great progress in restoring basic education services to its people, and education has received significantly increased resources over the last decade. Total enrollment in basic and secondary education has increased between 2002 and 2011 by 14.6 percent. The number of teachers more than doubled during the same period. There have been significant improvements in school infrastructure and facilities, as well as progress in central government management and institutional capacity. The introduction of the Basic School cluster-based reform provided the opportunity for a major shift in accountability and autonomy at the school level. It also supports schools to address major service delivery constraints through their own strengthened community-based management. For instance, the reformed School Feeding program shifts the focus of program solutions from central to sub-national levels, in which communities can start playing an important role. School grants have led to the abolition of school fees and have supported school-based management reforms and increased school autonomy. At the same time, a new teacher career regime was approved due the need to introduce qualification and competency standards linked to career progression, salary increases and teacher accountability. Although government has focused on and invested in access to education, there are still large access gaps, particularly between urban and rural areas. Student absenteeism is also a major cause for concern. Key driving factors are related to inadequate school infrastructure and facilities, affordability of education and few opportunities for non-formal and second chances education programs. In addition, poor learning outcomes of Timorese students is a major area of weakness. Results from a early grade reading assessment conducted in 2011 show that in Grade 1, only 3 percent of students attained a basic oral reading fluency benchmark (45 correct words per minute (CW). Among Grade 2 students, only 14 percent of students were able to read at that level. While system performance is discouraging, the assessment also showed that success is possible: at the end of Grade 3, 61 percent of students are able to read at the benchmark. Results from Early Grade Mathematics Assessment conducted in 2011 reveal that math problems involving reasoning presented difficulties to around 77 percent of Grade 2 and 62 percent of Grade 3 students. Only about a third of students in Grade 1 could solve simple additions. In general, poor learning results are associated mainly to teachers' low qualifications, high proportion of voluntary teachers, high levels of teacher absenteeism, lack of pre-service teachers training of teachers, major teacher retirement looming and lack of textbooks and learning materials. High repetition rates, especially among early graders, low reading ability and difficulties with simple math reasoning problems remain very problematic. Improvement of quality of education in Timor Leste requires a series of efforts including ensuring that comprehensive sets of policies enabling such improvement to happen. The Systems Approach for Better Education Results (SABER) has been used as a tool evaluate the quality of education policies against evidence-based global standards, using new diagnostic tools and detailed policy data collected for the initiative. In addition to SABER analysis in 4 dimensions, teacher policy, school autonomy and accountability, student assessment and workforce development carried out in 2012-2013, SABER analysis on ECD and Engaging Private Sector (EPS) will be used to more comprehensively support the effort to improve quality of education in Timor Leste. Research has proven the importance of investing in ECD. Children who participate in well-conceived ECD programs tend to be more successful in later school, are more competent socially and emotionally, and show higher verbal and intellectual development during early childhood than children who are not enrolled in high quality programs. However, ECD presents a particular challenge to policymakers due to its multi-sectoral nature and the need to reach out to a variety of stakeholders. SABER-ECD will provide policymakers in Timor Leste with tools and analysis to identify policy reforms that can promote healthy and robust development for all children during their early years. Partnership with private sector in education can maximize the potential for expanding equitable access to schooling and for improving education outcomes, especially for marginalized groups. This is an important policy area in Timor Leste. While basic education remains a public responsibility, the government can explore and use a variety of models for financing and providing high-quality education services that promote equity goals. SABER-Engaging Private Sector will provides guidance on how to ensure that the work of non-state providers helps meet national education goals Reliable evidence is needed to design policies that will allow overcoming Timor-Leste's remaining challenges in provision of quality education. Accordingly, the first school survey was conducted in Timor-Leste in 2012. The second school survey is planned for 2015 to inform the policy makers about changes have been in place at school level and further efforts/reforms needed to improve service delivery. Education system will ultimately be demanded to contribute to productivity. Study on Skills Toward Employment and Productivity (STEP) will inform the policy makers on the skills constraints inhibiting the supply of the skills demanded by the labor market.
Project title: P150515/TF017149: Improving the Quality of Education

Project Description: Activity aims to: (1) to influence policy debate over appropriateness and adequacy of the current social protection policy, (2) to support development of the Bolsa da Mae CCT program and (3) inform and influence parametric and structural design of the civil service and national pension schemes. The activity is outlined as follows (for further details see supplemental information): Component 1: Dialogue over the social protection policy This component will focus on communicating the broader needs for social protection reform, namely, to (1) respond to vast exclusion of majority of poor from the safety nets (2) to enhance promotional value of social assistance. In large part this will be attempted through presentations to the MoF's Consultative Council on Finance Management, MoF's technical working group on social protection, the directors and the Minister of MSS, the inter-ministerial pensions working group. Also includes technical support to the NSO for the revision of the national household survey questionnaire to create capacity for empirically driven SP policy decision-making. Component 2: Bolsa da Mae reform The second component of the proposed AAA aims to improve performance and efficiency of Bolsa da Mae CCT (BdM) program. Discussions with the MSS have identified specific interest for TA in (1) assessing the adequacy of the BdM benefit structure, and (2) on assessing the effectiveness of verification mechanisms for CCT compliance. The two notes will rely on desk review of international practice, review of operational manuals, field visits to interview beneficiaries/social animators and analysis of the 2011 household income and expenditure survey. The MSS also requested a diagnostic report for improving operational processes of the Bolsa da Mae program. The resulting assessment(s) are expected to become the core input in designing a comprehensive reform action plan by the MSS. The task aims to develop a partnership with the UNDP which will involve coordinating over the TORs for the UNDP and World Bank consultants undertaking the review, consulting over the emerging findings and policy messages and potentially jointly releasing a single study or a set of coordinated reports. Finally, the MSS is looking for assistance to develop community sessions for promoting good parenting practices among BdM program beneficiaries. To this end the team is proposing to partner with the UNICEF who will be responsible for delivering the background study of current needs, mapping of existing programs and a proposal for educational content with the operational framework. The Bank SP team which has a comparative advantage over the Bolsa da Mae will provide continuous feedback to the UNICEF consultants to ensure that the study is relevant and the resulting proposal can interface with the operational systems of the Bolsa da Mae program. Component 3: Pensions As per the advice provided by the World Bank during the previous FY the Ministry of Finance would like to repeal and replace the civil service pension law as it deems it too broad in scope, coverage and cost. To that end, the Ministry of Finance had requested assistance to provide detailed feedback on major articles of the pension law, focusing on what this law does, how it might be amended and the attendant financial implications of the amendment. The Ministry of Finance also requested for a policy paper that reviews international experience in dealing with multiple objectives, namely: civil servants retirement, severance options and integration with national social security plan. This task will also include just-in-time advisory services to the MoF and the MSS on the emerging national social security scheme.
Project title: P147353/BB: Dialogue and TA for improved social protection policy

Project Description: ADB-funded projects in Timor-Leste have validated the need to improve operations and maintenance (O&M) of water systems and to increase institutional capacity to manage urban water supply systems. These needs are vital to adequate service delivery, which cannot be compensated for through infrastructure investment alone. A different operational mode with an effective O&M strategy is required for Timor-Leste to meet its water sector development goals. Previous TAs have focused on changing the National Directorate for Water Supply and Sanitation (DNSAS) management structure without addressing the constraints posed by the existing regulatory and institutional framework. Within the current framework, DNSAS does not have the mandate to implement the proposed management structures and procedural changes. The TA will be linked to the proposed ADB-funded District Capitals Water Supply Project that will rehabilitate the urban water supply systems of Pante Macasar and Manatuto, and introduce the use of public-private partnerships (PPPs) for service provision, in the form of management contracts for the O&M of the rehabilitated systems for a period of two years. The TA will help to achieve and sustain the expected impact and outcome of the proposed project. Particularly, it will provide water sector officials at the national level and in Manatuto and Pante Macasar with the capacity and institutional reforms needed to effectively manage, operate, and maintain urban water supply systems, including catchment area management. Lessons learned from the TA will inform the national roll-out of a new urban water sector management system for Timor-Leste, which can serve as model for the reform of other infrastructure sectors.
Project title: TA 7981: Strengthening Water Sector Management and Service Delivery

Project Description: Timor-Leste is exposed to natural hazards, including flooding, drought, typhoons, wave surges, earthquakes and tsunamis. Climatologists project that the weather in the region is likely to become hotter and drier, leading to drought and causing rainfall to become heavier and erratic, causing more flooding. The low-lying atolls within the region are also highly susceptible to climate change phenomena such as sea level rise, coastal erosion and coral bleaching. There is now substantial evidence to indicate that the changes in weather conditions associated with climate change will increase the likelihood and intensity of recurrent natural disasters throughout the country. The country experiences cyclical effects of the El Nio/Southern Oscillation (ENSO)-related weather anomalies. Floods have resulted in decreased agricultural production, damage to infrastructure, and particularly in heavy flood-affected locations, displacement of communities and loss of property and livelihoods. In cases of flooding, watershed behaviour is associated with disasters affecting lives and livelihoods. The combination of heavy monsoonal rains and steep topography make many parts of the country prone to floods, landslides and river shifts. Prevalent deforestation leading to erosion compounds the likelihood of landslides and builds up sediment in the rivers exacerbating river shifting and flooding. Poor road design and drainage also worsens flooding and landslides. Although casualties have not been of high proportion in the rainy season, severe disruption to road networks cuts off community access to markets and contributes to food insecurity. The levels of disaster risk are compounded by poverty, socio-economic and environmental imbalances. Practicalities such as either rugged terrain or remoteness also leave many disaster-prone communities isolated from resources and assistance. In addition, low levels of development in Timor Leste, multiply the disaster risk faced by this nation thereby eroding the gains of existing poverty reduction programmes, which challenges it in achieving the Millennium Development Goals (MDG). Evidently, past disasters have led to water and food security issues, health concerns, as well, impeded hard-won development gains. In spite of these impacts and hazard-prone nature of the affected communities, formalized disaster risk reduction (DRR) initiatives have yet to be effectively fostered at national and sub-national levels. While there have in recent past been certain level of engagement of international actors, such as AusAID and UNDP working at the national level in Timor-Leste, there has also been some dynamic agencies, with the appropriate knowledge and expertise, working in partnership with local governments and NGOs at the grassroots level. While some at-risk communities, particularly those in more isolated settlements, pursue informal disaster management activities of a traditional and indigenous nature, this local knowledge is not being appropriately harnessed and community vulnerability to disasters is still present. In sum, there is a general lack of understanding and awareness of natural hazards, climate change and disaster preparedness and adaptation within the communities ?
Project title: Disaster Risk Reduction through Building Community Resilience in Timor-Leste - CS.0426

Project Description: The Mud Crab and Fish Cultivation (MCFC) Project aims to develop aquaculture enterprise through improved technical capacity at household and community levels. MCFC works with the National Directorate for Fisheries and Aquaculture in the Ministry of Agriculture (MAF) to support aquaculture development in Liquica, Dili, Manatuto, Baucau, Lautem and Manufahi Districts. MCFC provides technical assistance and training assistance in mud crab and fish cultivation to coastal communities living adjacent to mangrove areas. The project additionally develops small-scale aquaculture business through producer groups. Technical and training support is directed at producer groups who demonstrate a strong interest and desire to diversify their source of revenue and invest in aquaculture as a livelihood. The program further links producers to domestic markets, and work with buyers, traders and producer groups to develop business linkages. The project is using a value chain approach with public and private sector partners to build aquaculture enterprise and trade through high value products and increase new income opportunities for rural households. Aquaculture Approach: MCFC organizes the producer groups within each location to start-up mud crab production by fattening crabs or growing out and selling to local markets where there is a growing market demand. Other assistance includes sourcing wild crabs, feeding and construction of cages, pens and grow out pond systems, using mostly local materials. Crab producers are taught that mud crabs should be fattened to between 600 and 800 grams of body weight. Mud crabs are sold locally to supermarkets and tourist-oriented restaurants and hotels Hatchery: To ensure the long-term sustainability of crab farming and fishing activities, the MCFC project intends to build a small-scale hatchery in collaboration with MAF in order to produce and hatch seed stock for viable crab production. The hatchery stages include egg, Zoeal and Megalopa, up to crablets. MAF will own, manage and operate the hatchery. Environment: Through its mapping and survey process, the MCFC program examines the habitat and suitability of mangrove areas and takes reasonable steps to ensure that the mangroves are not degraded by mud crab or fish production. Training and technical materials include awareness information concerning the use of mangrove areas.
Project title: Mud Crab and Fish Cultivativation

Project Description: The Support for Civil Service Reform (SCSR) project was signed September 2006 and commenced in January 2007. Several initiatives under the SCSR project were begun with Personnel Management Information System (PMIS) and the Temporary Advisory Services Initiative Fund (TASI Fund). However, support to the development of civil service subsidiary legislation and human resource development activities were slow to begin. Changes in Government (and the machinery of government) and increasing areas of support from other development partners in public administration have necessitated a review of the project document. Whilst the broad objectives of the original project document remain valid there has been a need to refocus several aspects of the project design to minimise potential overlap and to address emerging needs and gaps of the Government's capacity.

Project Description: Timor-Leste held national presidential and legislative elections in 2007 and will hold local elections in 2008. The 2007 elections were the first national post-independence elections organized by the Timorese and as such represent an important step in the consolidation of democracy in the country. The elections were administered by the Technical Secretariat for Electoral Administration (STAE) and supervised by the National Electoral Commission (CNE). The three national electoral processes, Presidential (2 rounds) and Parliamentarian, were considered in general by the stakeholders to have been free, fair and in line with international standards and national laws. The national electoral bodies were assisted by technical assistance made available by this project and the United Nations Integrated Mission in Timor-Leste (UNMIT). Based on the lessons learned throughout this demanding process and in view of the need to strengthen the human and institutional capacity of the national electoral management bodies, political parties and the media, this project has been revised for its second phase to provide longer-term support following the 2007 national elections and using an Electoral Cycle Approach. The second phase of the project will work with the electoral institutions (CNE and STAE) and the political parties to build capacities, and will work on issues of legal reform and civic education to ensure open and participative electoral processes. In so doing, the project aims to establish a framework for international assistance for the Timorese electoral cycle, coordinate international donor support, target funds and services more effectively and avoid duplication of resources. Where the focus of the first phase of the project was on 'hard' or material assistance, the focus of the second phase is on 'soft' or human capacity and institution building assistance. The project will serve as the umbrella for all UN electoral assistance, whether it is being channeled through UNDP or provided through UNMIT's mandate.
Project title: Support to the Timorese Electoral Cycle (00053311)

Project Description: This project Strengthening Civilian Oversight and Management Capacity in the Security Sector builds on support to the Government of Timor-Leste between 2008-2010 under the Security Sector Review/Capacity Development Facility project. It supports National Priority no. 7 on 'Public Safety & Security', the 2030 Strategic Plan of the Secretariat of State for Security, the 2010-2014 Strategic Plan of the National Parliament, and Force 2020 of the Secretariat of State for Defense. The objective of the project is to strengthen Timor-Leste's security sector for sustained peace and stability in the country and for its citizens through: (1) enhanced civilian oversight and management capacity in priority areas identified by national partners, and (2) improved research and training capacity in the security sector. It will provide technical assistance for policy oversight, legal and institutional development and capacity building in the Parliament, the Secretariats of State for Defence and Security; and the Office of the President. In line with UNMIT's Integrated Strategic Framework and Transition Plan (towards expected UNMIT drawdown in 2012), UNDP and UNMIT will work closely together on the implementation of this project. Coordination will be made with related projects, namely the UNDP-OHCHR support to the Provedoria for Human Rights and Justice and the UNDP support to the National Parliament.
Project title: Strengthening Civilian Oversight and Management Capacity in the Security Sector (00078949)
Donor Agency: - Office of the President - United Nations Development Programme

Project Description: Two years after the country fell into the crisis in April 2006, 5,963 families have received assistance to leave IDP camps and return or relocate; whilst 9,937 families remain registered with the government as future beneficiaries for assistance (MSS, August 2008). To address the IDP issues and more broadly early recovery challenges in a comprehensive and coordinated manner, the Government of Timor-Leste adopted the National Recovery Strategy (NRS) in December 2007. While a range of initiatives to support the NRS are underway, there is still a significant gap in promoting early recovery and durable solutions to the IDP population. With the current progress achieved on the return and reintegration, of IDPs and the gradual decommissioning of camps, these solutions have become the more essential for insuring sustainable returns and mitigating any risk of conflict in already strained communities. Against this background, the project aims to strengthen early recovery efforts through (1) developing mechanisms and processes to meet the needs of the IDP-receiving communities; and (2) augmenting early recovery coordination capacity to implement the NRS and the National Priorities Plan (NPP). It will complement the ongoing UNDP support to the community dialogue process as well as enhance national and international coordination effort in early recovery.
Project title: Strengthening Early Recovery for Comprehensive and Sustainable Reintegration of IDPs (SERC) (00063615)
Donor Agency: - Government of Australia - Government of Sweden - United Nations Development Progremme (JPAA)

Project Description: This project, Strengthening National Police Capacity in Timor-Leste, is intended to strengthen the capacities of the Timorese National Police (PNTL) to deliver quality policing services to the population of Timor-Leste following resumption of executive policing over the national territory in March 2011, and to maintain stability during the potentially sensitive period of the 2012 national elections and later after UNMIT draw-down. The project will also inform UNDP future interventions for supporting capacity development of the PNTL. It aims to (1) develop PNTL management and administration capacity; (2) enhance its training capacity; (3) strengthen its internal oversight mechanisms; and (4) provide technical assistance to the Secretariat of State for Security (SoSS) to finalize the PNTL promotions regime. Close coordination will be facilitated with the ongoing UNDP-OHCHR project supporting the Provedor's Office, the UNDP Justice programme and the Secretariat of State for Security to enhance coordination and complementarities among the various actors. The project is in line with the UNMIT Transition Plan, which provides a road map for hand-over of UNMIT responsibilities and support functions to relevant partner institutions both within and outside the UN. UNDP has been included as possible partner to the Government in all UNMIT focus areas, including Police and Security.
Project title: Strengthening the National Police Capacity in Timor-Leste (00079620)
Donor Agency: - Norway - United Nations - United Nations Development Programme

Project Description: The LMI Department, with technical assistance from the ILO, is responsible for collecting and disseminating labour market information and operationalizing the computerised labour market information database (SIMU). SEFOPE is expanding its employment-support programme to the country's all 13 districts. In 2009, the initiatives include the youth employment promotion programme and the employment-intensive infrastructure programme. Towards an effective implementation of these programmes two twin challenges are facing the Government of Timor-Leste: 1) the lack of reliable employment data and 2) the need for improved SIMU's functionalities and continued training to LMI Department staff. The project "Timor-Leste Labour Market Information Systems Project - Phase I Extension (July - December 2009)" will provide technical assistance to the Government of Timor-Leste in the conduct of the Labour Force Survey and the dissemination of its results and continues training to the staff of the SEFOPE in the collection, management, and dissemination of labour market information.
Project title: Labour Market Information Systems - Extension

Project Description: Good governance of the labour market is essential for the creation of decent work for all and to build paths out of poverty. The availability and dissemination of labour market information is a fundamental element to allow effective and efficient organization of the employment services, promote the smooth functioning of the labour market and stimulate development. This is the background against which the Timor-Leste Labour Market Information System (LMI) Project was designed. It aims to build the capacity of the SEFOPE to provide IT and Management Information Systems support to the National Directorate of Employment and National Directorate of Vocational Training, and labour market information to the Government of Timor-Leste and other stakeholders as required. The present initiative builds on the outputs of the LMI Systems Project funded by the Irish Aid since December 2006, of which the assistance was central to establish a Labour Market Information Department within SEFOPE and to create an embryonic national capacity in such a specific and technically demanding area. Since its inception, the LMI Systems Project has been representing a resources centre that provides crucial support services to other employment creation and skills development initiatives implemented under the organizational framework of the SEFOPE, contributing decisively to the improvement of their outreach and impact. It enables SEFOPE to take informed decisions on the new directions for the Timor-Leste Vocational Training System, on the measures to stimulate closer articulation with employers, to improve job mediation, to promote self-employment, livelihoods and temporary employment, and to establish Career Guidance services. Just taking as reference the period starting from January 2008, the programmes assisted by the LMI Project provided Career Guidance to 13,731 clients (51.9% women and 74.1% youth) of the Employment and Career Guidance Centres (CEOPs), approved 99 community proposals in all the 13 districts of Timor-Leste creating training and self-employment opportunities for 3,469 women (77.6%) and men job and training seekers, and generated 1,827,795 workerdays of employment that provided 58,305 workers (27% women and 48.3% youth) in rural areas with temporary jobs and income. Despite the remarkable progress achieved, SEFOPE still requires further assistance to overcome some remaining issues such as the need to improve the articulation between information customers and producers, improve the quality of the data, enhance the use of existing sources of LMI and address critical data gaps. The current 18-months extension of the LMI Project will allow to complete the development and installation of the new SIMU Web (SEFOPE computerized Labour Market Information system) in the 5 Employment and Career Guidance Centres of the districts of Baucau, Bobonaro, Dili, Ermera and Oecusse, and to finalise and release the findings of the first post-independence Timor-Leste Labour Force Survey. Other fundamental labour market information will be also produced and disseminated, while consolidating the capacity of the LMI Department of SEFOPE.
Project title: Labour Market Information System Project

Project Description: The project will undertake a systematic mapping and cataloging of sites situated along the corridor of the Dili-Ainaro road that will benefit from the Timor- Leste Road Climate Resilience Project. The research will treat sites from the Portuguese colonial era and Indonesian occupation era, as well as important sites related to local custom (such as sacred houses). In addition to physical structures, the research will also address natural sites with cultural significance (such as sacred forests and waterways), and will survey existing cultural groups active near the sites (such as traditional dance groups). The project will involve the identification of heritage sites in consultation with community members and in cooperation with the State Secretariat of Arts and Culture. The locations of sites will be GIS mapped, including reference to access roads and distances from public services. The catalog will include information on the type and condition of sites, as well as an anthropological analysis of local communities ' understandings of the sites' meaning and purpose. The research results will be used to inform development of a policy note and of user-friendly checklists that will encourage and facilitate culturally sensitive use and/or protection of such sites in the context of infrastructure development activities.
Project title: P130713/TF012328 - Road for Cultural Heritage - TA

Project Description: The objective of the Education Sector Support Program for Timor-Leste is to strengthen the capacity of the Ministry for effective policy development, resource management, and innovation. Component one: capacity building for policy, planning and program development. This component will develop Ministry of Education and Culture (MoEC) capacity in policy, planning and program development via the production of policy advisory notes and two sub-sector strategies, and via workshops, the establishment of a National Commission for Academic Assessment and Accreditation, and through technical assistance in procurement and financial management, monitoring and evaluation, school grants monitoring and program design. Component two: learning materials. This component will assist MoEC to develop and operationalize its textbook and learning materials policies and will also assist the MoEC to finance the provision of the quality learning materials for primary and pre-secondary schools. Component three: Construction/rehabilitation design and quality assurance. This component will ensure the quality and cost-effectiveness of the government-financed school construction and rehabilitation program. Component four: work skills for pre-secondary students. This component will support, the development and piloting of a pre-secondary curriculum module for developing work skills and attributes via community enhancement projects. On top of the four component above, is also helping MoE by undertaking Early Grade Reading Achievemnet (EGRA). AusAID activity 07A917 & 07A919.

Project Description: The violence of 2006 and 2007 caused the displacement of up to 150,000 people to makeshift camps across the country, and the destruction of over 8,000 houses in the capital Dili. The Government's response, the National Recovery Strategy, included the provision of compensa-tion for damage and destruction to houses and goods, known as the HHU programme. This was divided into two phases; Phase I awarded payments of up to USD 4,500 based on the level of house destruction, while a further 500 USD was given to claimants who lost goods during the crisis, known as Phase II. While it was envisaged that HHU would close in the early months of 2010, by July 2010, there remained a residual caseload of around 300 cases pending process and payment under Phase I. Moreover, the Government requested that MSS process an additional 5,000 cases of families who had allegedly missed the original registration, but had approached the Govern-ment through local authorities, other government institutions, and the Church. During the budget rectification in June and July 2010, the National Parliament approved an additional USD 4.1 million for MSS to complete the programme and any issues relating to the 2006 and 2007 crises by the end of 2010. This deadline was set by the National Parliament, as condition to approving the additional budget as above mentioned. Until July 2010, IOM had provided technical support to MSS and HHU, facilitating the payment of recovery packages1 for 16,478 families and the closure of 65 IDP camps. IOM provision of technical support was crucial to establish administrative systems, to increase understanding of the different components of the programme, and to deliver technically based un-biased recommendations and advice on the challenges faced during the programme's implementation. Therefore, to facilitate the smooth workflow of cases necessary to meet the National Parlia-ment's deadline, and based on IOM's previous support to the implementation of HHU, MSS requested IOM's continued support and presence at MSS. This request gave rise to various challenges, not least of which was the short timeframe to register, verify and process the additional cases by the end of the year. MSS also highlighted concerns that a faster process of cases without additional support could potentially increase potential for abuse of the system, and required support to take complete control of the admin-istrative systems and procedures accompanying HHU. To this end, IOM provided support to: the core evaluation process whereby family claims were registered, verified and, if appropri-ate, provided with recovery packages; to differentiate between valid and fraudulent claims; and to conduct capacity building to ensure national ownership and sustainability of the admin-istrative procedures.
Project title: Building houses together" program TL10 DP.0530

Project Description: Specific project activity will focus on building agribusiness training capacity within high schools under the administrative jurisdiction of East Timor's Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (MAFF), located at Fuiloro, in the eastern part of the country, Natarbora in the central region and Maliana in the western region, through the development of a one-year post-high school certificate program in agribusiness. Programs at each school will share a common standardized core agribusiness curriculum. In addition, each school will have an associated operating agribusiness that will be used as a training tool for the students. The type of business and technical emphasis at each school is as follows:  At Fuiloro, Land O'Lakes will build on the school's existing capacity in dairy production to develop a small but sustainable value-added dairy products business. Training will be provided to faculty and students in market research, dairy processing and sales. Initial strategy will focus on import substitution within the Dili dairy products market, targeting retail and institutional buyers.  At Natarbora, Land O'Lakes will develop an apiculture (beekeeping and honey production) business at the school and use this as a working model to train students in agribusiness management and market development. Marketing efforts will focus on Dili area supermarkets and shops.  At Maliana, Land O'Lakes will develop a horticultural business that focuses on producing irrigated high value fruits and vegetables for the Dili market. This is a small-scale business, but can incorporate all of the elements of a commercial enterprise, and can act as a teaching model. As a foundation to the above activities, Land O'Lakes will develop a standardized core agribusiness curriculum at the three schools with emphasis on developing skills in bookkeeping, management, agribusiness financial modeling, marketing, credit, business law/regulations and ethics. Agribusiness skills will be further refined by the use of agribusiness case studies and comprehensive agribusiness plans prepared by the students prior to graduation. The combination of exposure to actual business operations (through the dairy, apiculture and horticulture businesses at the schools), along with research and study of operating businesses will prepare graduates to become proficient technicians, entry-level managers and entrepreneurs within East Timor's agricultural sector. The activity plan assumes that every year, 50 students from each school will graduate from the one year (comprised of four quarters of instruction) agribusiness certificate program. Total output of all three schools will be 150 students per year, beginning 18 months after program start-up. The total investment by USAID will be $3,000,000 USD. Assuming that the investment in curriculum and school-agribusiness development is amortized over a ten-year period (and 1,500 graduates), the cost per program graduate will be approximately $2,000 USD. Additionally, the activity will train approximately 30 faculty members in a variety of agribusiness subjects.
Project title: Building Agribusiness Capacity in East Timor
Donor Agency: United States Agency for International Development

Project Description: The aim of this project is to support a coordinated approach to capacity-building on counter trafficking in Timor-Leste and empower concerned governmental and national non-governmental organizations to develop an effective, multi-pronged approach to the trafficking phenomenon in Timor-Leste, in line with the Government of Timor-Leste priority policy to fight this phenomenon and ensure protection of victims. During this project's implementation, IOM will design specific training curricula, which will provide a deeper understanding of human trafficking, including concepts and definitions, and practical activity-based guidelines on how to address and manage counter-human trafficking activities across the key areas of prevention, protection and prosecution. Based on these curricula, IOM will organise seven 5-day training workshops. Participants will be drawn from MSS Headquarters and districts including those in the department of child protection, and civil society organisations' staff already working in shelters, namely PRADET. Apart from these specific training sessions, IOM will conduct onsite mentoring activities as required to both trained MSS and civil society staff including in the districts. In addition to enhancing the knowledge and capacity of participants on trafficking and how to concretely undertake counter trafficking activities, the project will launch a survey on irregular migration, including irregular entry, trafficking in persons and smuggling of migrants in Timor-Leste. The survey is based on the work carried out by the ACP Observatory with the national institutions in Timor-Leste.
Project title: Strengthening Government and Service providers responses to Human Trafficking in Timor Leste - CT.0576

Project Description: The EMM-II project in East Timor was designed to respond to an environment of fundamen-tal organisational change, as the government implemented the decision to establish the Migra-tion Service as an autonomous agency outside the national police force. In addition, GoET had indicated a desire to undertake a revision of the Immigration and Asylum Law under which the migration agencies operate. In the context of this fundamental reform, the following seven themes were identified as areas of focus for the EMM-II project from 2009 to 2011: 1. Successful establishment of the Migration Service as a non-police agency; 2. Improved border processing using a risk-based approach; 3. Improved management and planning skills for senior officers; 4. Improved visa processing and higher quality decision-making; 5. Implementation of an integrated border management system; 6. Improved inter-agency coordination; and 7. Training and ongoing support. This report provides information on project activities undertaken in the fourth period from 1 September 2010 to 31 March 2011.
Project title: Enhancing Migration Management Project in Timor Leste (EMM II) - TC.0336
Donor Agency: Australian Department of Immigration and Citizenship

Project Description: Despite the efforts undertaken by the UN and the Government of Timor-Leste (GoTL) to address gender inequalities since the independence of Timor-Leste in 1999, there are still outstanding issues that need to be addressed in a holistic way to improve the conditions of women and girls. The outstanding problems are as follows: _ Women and girls are still vulnerable to violence and internal conflict, particularly in relation to gender-based violence and human trafficking. Existing lacunas in the legislative framework and service delivery have had a detrimental effect on women and girl's security and well-being. _ Little to no social services is in place to respond to victims of violence, exploitation and abuse, including women and girls, especially in rural areas. _ Women and girls are still discriminated against in the areas of health, education and economic development with government services and opportunities not responding appropriately to their needs and with little allocation of resources to guarantee this. _ Women and girls from female-headed households in poverty-stricken districts and trafficking-prone areas are less likely to benefit from traditional forms of social safety nets, thus increasing their vulnerability. _ Lack of sex-disaggregated data in all sectors remains a major problem. The proposed Joint Programme (JP) "Supporting Gender Equality and Women's Rights in Timor-Leste" is a three-year programme that supports the GoTL to improve the conditions of women and girls in Timor-Leste through the protection of their rights and their empowerment. It offers them fair access to social and economic resources by increasing their access to entitlements and rights. The JP has been developed and will be implemented by five UN agencies in partnership with government agencies and structures at national and district levels and in collaboration with relevant civil society organisations and individuals to build institutional capacity to address the above problems. The JP will support an environment to establish legal frameworks to end domestic violence and human trafficking by enabling women and girls to claim their rights. These legal frameworks establish norms, standards and practices for the GoTL to operationalise programmes i.e. services, outreach mechanisms, social protection scheme to reduce vulnerability of women and girls as well as improving protection for them. The JP also focuses on budget as an influential policy instrument of the government to ensure government's financial commitment to programmes that will impact on the lives of women and girls. This is in line with the current priorities of the GoTL in social protection and solidarity by improving social service delivery though national planning of the budget and execution for performance and accountability.
Project title: Supporting Gender Equality - Timor Leste CT.0334

Project Description: IOM recognises that while IDPs from tented camps have returned to their communities, many of the issues which led to the 2006 crisis remain unresolved; the Community Stabilisation Project under this financing decision aimed to minimise these potential conflict sources. The project comprised three components: to build and rehabilitate community infrastructures; to produce and disseminate a best practice house construction manual; and, to produce an educational soap opera. In communities strongly affected by the 2006 crisis, the project provided assistance to the government with the construction and rehabilitation of small-scale community infrastructures to mitigate potential conflicts caused by competition for resources. These small-scale infrastructures were built in four high-risk sucos (villages), in Dili, and were selected through IDP Return Monitoring findings carried out by IOM, in consultation with several partners and the beneficiary communities. In Timor-Leste most families build their own houses, often without the necessary technical skills. The production of a housing manual aimed to provide user-friendly, safe and healthy house construction advice to support primarily returning IDPs who build or re-build their houses. In order to initiate a process of national reflection on a variety of social issues linked to the 2006 crisis, the project produced and arranged for the broadcasting of an educational soap opera (telenovela) on both radio and television. Other reflection issues were also included in this soap opera, such as domestic violence, regionalism, land property, elections and the generation gap.
Project title: Enhancing Stabilisation through Sustainable Reintegration of IDPS CS.0140

Project Description: Component 1: Mother-and-Child Health and Nutrition: Health Volunteers Rice incentive scheme. The new WFP Country Programme supports the national MCHN programme led by the Ministry of Health's Nutrition Department by focusing on preventing chronic under-nutrition during the window of opportunity from pregnancy to 23 months and on treating moderate acute malnutrition among children 24-59 months and PLW, through health facilities. The aim is to reach about 100,000 beneficiaries, to be targeted gradually until 2013. Each beneficiary receives at the health facilities a monthly take-home ration of fortified blended food (Timor Vita or imported CSB+ & oil). This service is expected to be provided by the staff Ministry of Health at the health centres and health posts, but since they are many times overloaded with the implementation of more than ten different programmes, volunteers from the community support facilitate in the handling and storage of food. They receive the food, provide appropriate storage conditions for the food received and facilitate in its distribution and recording. With support of WFP the storage facilities are being improved, but the majority are still very poor and still many health facilities don't have any, they rely on the neighbours good-will. The condition of the buildings/structures is very weak so a lot of attention has to be paid to the food storage. Food distribution in most cases takes place at the facility level. However, since many beneficiaries can't reach the health centre or health post very often due to the distance, road conditions, lack of transport, services timetable, work, etc, SISCa is being used as an important site to screen for the programme and to distribute food. In order to sustain this activity at SISCa level, a person needs to join the team to keep the food, and do the proper distribution to beneficiaries identified by the health staff. All these beneficiaries have to be recorded on site, and reported afterwards. All these "backstage" segments of the programme implementation are time consuming and require attention, and without having a person/volunteer specifically engaged and motivated for these tasks, the implementation of the programme becomes limited. On this regards, WFP supports the Ministry of Health in providing some incentive to keep and support these volunteers, by providing a monthly take-home ration of rice.
Project title: Health Volunteers Rice incentive Scheme

Project Description: The overall goal of the MDG-F Focus Country Initiative on Advocacy and Communications in Timor-Leste is to accelerate progress on the MDGs by de-mystifying the MDGs and raising awareness of the strong link between Timor-Leste's aspirations and the MDGs. This will be achieved by increasing awareness and support for the MDGs amongst policy makers and government workers and by increasing engagement with and appreciation of the MDGs amongst Timorese families. It is expected that these efforts will lead to further prioritization of the MDGs in national strategies, plans and budgets at the national level and to greater involvement by civil society groups and citizens in shaping the national MDG agenda. Since the Initiative commenced, it has also focused on supporting both of MDG-F Joint Programmes - the Joint Programme on Gender Equality and Women's Rights and the Joint Programme on Nutrition and Food Security - thus ensuring an integrated approach to the implementation of all the MDG-F supported activities in Timor-Leste.
Project title: MDG-F Focus Country Initiative on Advocacy and Communication

Project Description: The principal objectives of the MDG-F Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) Initiative in Timor-Leste are to support the implementation of the two joint programmes and to develop MDG monitoring and evaluation (M&E) capacities at national and district levels. The MDG M&E action plan includes activities to improve the M&E skills and competencies of Government staff and to assist them the establishment of M&E systems through practical guides for their implementation. The training will address the challenges of limited knowledge and skills of government officials with the focus on assessing progress towards the MDGs, including data collection and analysis, and how to use data for evidence-based policy development and decision making. The action plan also supports further development of the Timor-Leste DevInfo with the inclusion of MDG indicators in the database as well as training of government officials in the use of DevInfo. The updated DevInfo and the preparation of MDG indicators will be a key tool in the preparation of Timor-Leste's MDG Reports. Overall, the objectives of the MDG M&E Initiative are in line with the UNDAF as well as the National Priorities and the Timor-Leste Strategic Development Plan (2011-2030), thus seeking to strengthen the achievement of the MDGs, implementation of the Paris Declaration, the UN approach of "Delivering As One", and other national and international development objectives. Project Description: Since 2004 HAI has partnered with the Timor-Leste Ministry of Health (MOH) to strengthen public sector services for maternal care, newborn care, and family planning. HAI works with MOH staff at the central level of the MOH to develop activities and interventions that can benefit the country as a whole. HAI staff also supports the day-to-day activities of midwives and other health staff in six rural districts of the country. The production of two films educating women and their families about the benefits of prenatal care, delivery services and postnatal checkups, and family planning methods are being shown to rural community audiences throughout the country with a special airing on national television during the World Cup reaching an audience of roughly 200,000 people the majority of which were young men.

Project Description: The Prepara Ami ba ServisuÑ"Preparing ourselves for work"Ñprogram, known simply as "PAS", began as a response to the civil strife of 2006 and endeavored to groom youth for a formal job or small business ownership. The program focused on youth who had left school but not been able to find a position with a private sector firm. USAID's partner, the Education Development Center (EDC), developed a core curriculum that was then taught to trainers in a number of local NGOs. As a result of the PAS Program, most students were able to find acceptance as an intern or continue their studies in another institution after graduation.
Project title: Prepara Ami ba Servisu
